00:14:35,556 --> 00:14:40,460
is over it's it's finished it's been done it's complete already and the only reason that we

231
00:14:40,520 --> 00:14:45,023
don't leave a sudoku puzzle in this state is because it's kind of nicer when it's been tidied

232
00:14:45,123 --> 00:14:50,808
up um but that's not really how narratives are supposed to end we're not supposed to end narrative

233
00:14:50,868 --> 00:14:51,529
experiences

234
00:14:52,069 --> 00:14:59,514
with a process of tidying up particularly. Narratives are supposed to surprise and delight.

235
00:15:00,434 --> 00:15:05,857
Detective stories are supposed to have a big twist at the end, a big moment of revelation that clears

236
00:15:05,897 --> 00:15:10,420
away the confusion that came before, a moment where the light is suddenly shone. I mean you've

237
00:15:10,440 --> 00:15:15,023
never finished a Sudoku puzzle and finally put in that last number and thought, oh it was a five

238
00:15:15,063 --> 00:15:17,664
all along, of course I knew it, that changes everything.

239
00:15:19,388 --> 00:15:21,710
Sudoku will never generate that experience.

240
00:15:21,770 --> 00:15:23,572
It cannot generate that experience

241
00:15:23,632 --> 00:15:26,596
because it's fundamentally built not like that, right?

242
00:15:26,696 --> 00:15:28,157
So what am I talking about?

243
00:15:28,197 --> 00:15:29,739
I'm talking about the solve.

244
00:15:29,799 --> 00:15:30,680
We need the solve.

245
00:15:30,740 --> 00:15:31,681
Perhaps we need the solve.

246
00:15:31,781 --> 00:15:33,303
Anyway, we seem to be missing the solve.

247
00:15:35,058 --> 00:15:38,542
The master solution to the complex crime,

248
00:15:38,902 --> 00:15:42,746
the final pulling together of disparate elements

249
00:15:42,826 --> 00:15:46,109
to create something unexpected but ultimately completely

250
00:15:46,190 --> 00:15:46,690
sensible.

251
00:15:47,831 --> 00:15:51,595
Hercule Poirot does not solve a succession of small mysteries

252
00:15:51,715 --> 00:15:54,037
over the course of his one and a half hour TV

253
00:15:54,097 --> 00:15:55,319
movie from the 80s or his 200 page novel.

254
00:15:57,542 --> 00:15:59,583
with a hand the full narrative to him.

255
00:15:59,823 --> 00:16:00,943
That's not how he works.

256
00:16:00,983 --> 00:16:03,144
His process, which is a lot more dramatic,

257
00:16:03,864 --> 00:16:06,845
is that he brings together all the confusing and separate

258
00:16:06,905 --> 00:16:10,246
elements of the crime in a sunburst of solution

259
00:16:10,286 --> 00:16:13,066
that wows everybody, that floors everybody in the room.

260
00:16:13,867 --> 00:16:17,507
But as soon as he does it, we go, ah, we should have known.

261
00:16:17,628 --> 00:16:18,488
We should have known.

262
00:16:20,202 --> 00:16:21,282
So that's what I'm interested in.

263
00:16:21,342 --> 00:16:24,083
That's what I want to talk about today is how do we move away

264
00:16:24,203 --> 00:16:28,784
from this idea of the basic deductive game loop of the detective game

265
00:16:28,824 --> 00:16:32,385
to something that allows us these moments of blinding revelation

266
00:16:32,805 --> 00:16:34,746
that can climax a story for us?

267
00:16:34,786 --> 00:16:36,406
Can it can it be done? Can it be done?

268
00:16:36,646 --> 00:16:38,086
And of course, people have tried to do this, right?

269
00:16:38,126 --> 00:16:41,087
It's an obvious part of the murder mystery genre.

270
00:16:41,187 --> 00:16:43,287
It's classic. It's very, very classic.

271
00:16:44,248 --> 00:16:47,969
And one of the mechanics that's often used is the the fact

272
00:16:48,049 --> 00:16:49,709
linking deduction mechanic, right?

273
00:16:51,029 --> 00:16:54,071
The fact one plus fact two gives us exciting new fact three.

274
00:16:55,712 --> 00:17:01,995
Now, I want to talk about this mechanic specifically for a while, which...

275
00:17:03,318 --> 00:17:07,140
perhaps seems a bit unfair because it's just one mechanic amongst many,

276
00:17:07,601 --> 00:17:11,283
but I think it's got some really interesting flaws

277
00:17:11,523 --> 00:17:15,846
that are really helpful to think about sort of quite clearly.

278
00:17:17,327 --> 00:17:19,709
The first thing I want to say is that it's been tried by a lot of games.

279
00:17:19,749 --> 00:17:21,670
There's a lot of games that use this kind of mechanic.

280
00:17:21,710 --> 00:17:23,231
Some of them are more successful than others.

281
00:17:24,312 --> 00:17:26,754
And it's a pretty natural design to try, right?

282
00:17:26,894 --> 00:17:29,796
Logical deduction is A plus B implies C.

283
00:17:29,896 --> 00:17:30,016
So...

284
00:17:30,456 --> 00:17:32,859
That's pretty reasonable to think that this will work very well.

285
00:17:34,300 --> 00:17:38,845
And moreover, it comes directly from the detective game core loop.

286
00:17:39,365 --> 00:17:46,953
We have a fact. We take a combination lock style action of applying these two things that don't immediately appear connected together,

287
00:17:47,354 --> 00:17:50,257
demonstrating our understanding and the game unlock something for us.

288
00:17:50,297 --> 00:17:52,700
So it's a natural part of that game loop.

289
00:17:53,737 --> 00:18:00,701
But as I say, I think that the idea has some flaws which expose some flaws in our wider thinking about detective games, perhaps.

290
00:18:01,341 --> 00:18:05,924
Firstly, some fairly simple things. You actually have to have fact one and fact two.

291
00:18:06,024 --> 00:18:11,807
I don't just mean you have to have played the game enough to find them, but they also have to be things that you can pick up and put in your UI screen.

292
00:18:12,630 --> 00:18:25,755
So in a good detective story, the detective is frequently making deductions based on things like their understanding of human nature or the unspoken rules of social etiquette and not just the cigar butt found in the fireplace.

293
00:18:25,855 --> 00:18:33,418
It's a mixture of those two. Often a detective will go looking for additional weird information on the basis of some kind of.

294
00:18:34,721 --> 00:18:39,863
they've had which gets accumulated into their fact pile. In Christie's The Mysterious Affair

295
00:18:39,903 --> 00:18:44,424
at Stiles, Poirot baffles his associate Hastings by asking, by saying the most significant fact

296
00:18:44,464 --> 00:18:48,165
in the crime is that the temperature was 80 degrees in the shade the night before.

297
00:18:48,765 --> 00:18:54,027
Hastings is completely perplexed but it does improve indeed to be the clincher of the crime,

298
00:18:54,087 --> 00:19:00,489
it's obvious in retrospect. The problem then is not one of finding the answer, it's really one of

299
00:19:00,769 --> 00:19:03,890
asking the right question. But if you're doing a deduction linking game...

300
00:19:04,470 --> 00:19:08,452
your facts have to be up there in a way the player can access directly.

301
00:19:08,993 --> 00:19:13,955
You have to have the temperature on the night of April 15th written in a little box on the screen.

302
00:19:13,995 --> 00:19:17,556
You have to have, I don't know, ladies button their jackets right over left.

303
00:19:18,017 --> 00:19:22,379
And when you start to do that, it's a bit like when my son is eating an apple in the park

304
00:19:22,439 --> 00:19:26,220
and decides he wants to play I Spy for something beginning with an A.

305
00:19:28,281 --> 00:19:31,563
Secondly, the conclusion might not be that exciting.

306
00:19:32,260 --> 00:19:36,426
it's quite common to be playing one of these stories and be a little bit ahead of the narrative and think,

307
00:19:36,506 --> 00:19:37,608
oh, well, obviously this.

308
00:19:38,257 --> 00:19:43,138
and then wonder how you're supposed to tell the game this thing you already know.

309
00:19:43,278 --> 00:19:47,559
What weird and confusing process do I have to go through to explain something that's obvious to me?

310
00:19:47,579 --> 00:19:52,260
It's a very, very hard problem to avoid because of course people are differently versed in detective

311
00:19:52,280 --> 00:19:56,861
stories. Some things jump out, some things don't. It's deeply annoying both for the designer and

312
00:19:56,941 --> 00:20:02,063
the player. It's a real problem because of this combination lock gate that the player has to get

313
00:20:02,943 --> 00:20:06,504
But then again, what if the conclusion isn't obvious?

314
00:20:07,360 --> 00:20:09,361
What if it isn't immediately apparent?

315
00:20:09,861 --> 00:20:11,923
Then suddenly the fact that you've got all the facts

316
00:20:11,983 --> 00:20:13,704
of the case laid out in front of you,

317
00:20:13,744 --> 00:20:15,325
ready to be quickly linked together,

318
00:20:15,705 --> 00:20:17,326
scales up the possibilities in a way

319
00:20:17,367 --> 00:20:19,068
that isn't necessarily very fun.

320
00:20:19,488 --> 00:20:22,510
If there's no curation, then it can get very quick.

321
00:20:23,411 --> 00:20:26,992
overwhelming, even if the answer that you're looking for is completely fair and completely

322
00:20:27,032 --> 00:20:32,275
logical, and even if you understand the plot. That's a really crucial point, I think, actually.

323
00:20:32,635 --> 00:20:36,216
I wanted to give you an example, which is this. This is from a book called Where's the

324
00:20:36,276 --> 00:20:41,199
Pair by Britta Teckendrup, and it's a book that my children have. It's a book for toddlers,

325
00:20:41,719 --> 00:20:45,261
and it's surprisingly difficult. It's full of pages like this, which have a big picture,

326
00:20:45,861 --> 00:20:49,323
and you're supposed to spot the two matching fish.

327
00:20:50,123 --> 00:20:53,405
Now, if I could see you properly, you're a very tiny window on my computer screen.

328
00:20:54,065 --> 00:20:56,427
I would ask you to raise your hands when you see the pair.

329
00:20:57,287 --> 00:21:00,289
As it is, I'm going to wait for a bit, and I'm going to show you the answer.

330
00:21:00,609 --> 00:21:02,630
But perhaps you saw it immediately.

331
00:21:03,030 --> 00:21:04,871
Perhaps you already know exactly what it is.

332
00:21:05,812 --> 00:21:06,853
Or perhaps you're still looking.

333
00:21:07,593 --> 00:21:09,074
But I think we can agree on a couple of things.

334
00:21:09,134 --> 00:21:11,695
We can agree that as a problem, it's entirely fair.

335
00:21:12,216 --> 00:21:18,980
And the answer really should be completely, totally obvious.

336
00:21:19,350 --> 00:21:22,151
I mean, the answer is the two fish the other way.

337
00:21:22,711 --> 00:21:24,332
This should jump straight out to us.

338
00:21:25,052 --> 00:21:26,332
But I don't think it does.

339
00:21:26,352 --> 00:21:29,173
I find these pages of this book extremely difficult.

340
00:21:29,213 --> 00:21:30,354
I don't know whether you did or not.

341
00:21:31,034 --> 00:21:34,275
And I think that's because cross-referencing is hard,

342
00:21:34,555 --> 00:21:38,456
even if the rules for your cross-referencing are actually very simple.

343
00:21:38,976 --> 00:21:43,237
If the rules for what constitutes a match are actually a little bit obscure or opaque,

344
00:21:43,637 --> 00:21:47,198
then you end up with something that the player is going to attack by brute force out of sheer

345
00:21:47,258 --> 00:21:51,119
desperation, and we can't really fault them for that. The overwhelm problem is real.

346
00:21:52,539 --> 00:21:55,940
Now, I don't want to make it seem like I'm sitting here in my armchair, literally,

347
00:21:56,340 --> 00:21:59,921
criticizing a design that I've never tried. That would be a bit unfair. So I would like to add as

348
00:21:59,941 --> 00:22:05,782
well that at Inkle, we built around 20 or 30 deduction-based prototypes in the course of

349
00:22:05,802 --> 00:22:06,802
the last two or three years.

350
00:22:07,582 --> 00:22:11,824
and found, well we found even more problems and here are the other problems we found.

351
00:22:12,324 --> 00:22:16,426
Firstly it's cluttered, there's an enormous amount of information on screen but relative to it there's

352
00:22:16,446 --> 00:22:20,807
not actually that much for the player to do. It's a bit like the fish all had name labels

353
00:22:20,847 --> 00:22:24,689
and blurbs and a tooltip and you had to read all of them before you could see the structure.

354
00:22:25,469 --> 00:22:29,230
and sometimes you have to read them twice or three times and check back at them just to see what they said

355
00:22:29,270 --> 00:22:34,172
because you can't remember because there's so much text, all to click to matching things.

356
00:22:34,392 --> 00:22:38,773
The clutter gets worse as the game goes on rather than better because every time you

357
00:22:38,833 --> 00:22:42,274
make a deduction it makes another bloody fact and puts it in your fact list.

358
00:22:42,894 --> 00:22:45,356
unless the new facts somehow wipe out the old ones.

359
00:22:45,436 --> 00:22:48,159
But what if the old facts have multiple consequences?

360
00:22:48,239 --> 00:22:49,299
Truth isn't tidy.

361
00:22:49,380 --> 00:22:50,961
Things don't imply one thing.

362
00:22:51,001 --> 00:22:52,022
They imply lots of things.

363
00:22:52,442 --> 00:22:54,103
In fact, truth is a real, a real git

364
00:22:54,504 --> 00:22:57,266
because it's inherently broad, not narrow.

365
00:22:57,326 --> 00:23:00,589
I mean, the thing about truth is that it's true.

366
00:23:01,229 --> 00:23:09,117
there is never only one way to arrive at a truth or to deduce any fact, because truth abides,

367
00:23:09,357 --> 00:23:15,403
if you like. So while you can make a deduction game which allows you, I suppose, to arrive at

368
00:23:15,423 --> 00:23:19,187
truth in multiple ways, so that would get around that problem, but then you're putting even more

369
00:23:19,227 --> 00:23:22,750
facts on screen, some of which the player isn't going to use or is going to wonder why it's there

370
00:23:22,790 --> 00:23:24,893
because they got it over here in this other obvious way.

371
00:23:25,453 --> 00:23:30,739
And lastly, and this is very significant to me, it's hard to write. I mean, where does one fact

372
00:23:30,999 --> 00:23:37,726
end and another one begin? Is the fact Elsa is lying different from the fact Elsa is lying to

373
00:23:37,766 --> 00:23:43,572
protect Anna? Or is one a deduction from the other? Or is Anna knows Elsa is lying different

374
00:23:43,612 --> 00:23:47,336
from Elsa is lying or from Elsa is covering that Anna or...

375
00:23:48,694 --> 00:23:53,395
How do we know how best to chop our facts into tiny little atomic pieces?

376
00:23:54,256 --> 00:23:57,496
We're sort of guessing, but it gets very complex and muddy quite quickly.

377
00:23:57,837 --> 00:24:01,638
To all of this, Poirot says, no, and I agree with him.

378
00:24:01,778 --> 00:24:02,558
It is too much.

379
00:24:03,018 --> 00:24:05,679
So I think we need to look at the big solve concept from scratch.

380
00:24:05,699 --> 00:24:09,820
I think we need to take a step back and try and think from the beginning.

381
00:24:09,860 --> 00:24:11,640
What is it we actually want to achieve?

382
00:24:12,529 --> 00:24:16,292
keen in this climactic scene if we're going to really enjoy ourselves with some detective

383
00:24:16,512 --> 00:24:22,397
solving loveliness. So goals, great goals. What are our goals? Right, I want to be able to combine

384
00:24:22,457 --> 00:24:26,500
facts from the game. I want clues, I want discoveries, and I want to be able to combine

385
00:24:26,520 --> 00:24:29,883
them with ideas from the real world, with things that I know or intuitively believe.

386
00:24:31,324 --> 00:24:36,508
I want a curated input system so that I'm not overwhelmed at any point. I want just a few fish,

387
00:24:36,588 --> 00:24:38,329
not quite so many fish, thank you very much.

388
00:24:39,242 --> 00:24:43,944
I want to have some kind of input that makes it easy to express ideas.

389
00:24:43,984 --> 00:24:46,045
I don't want it to be too abstract or weird.

390
00:24:46,085 --> 00:24:49,086
I don't want to be drawing funny diagrams to try and explain something

391
00:24:49,106 --> 00:24:53,148
which doesn't naturally fit that particular presentation model.

392
00:24:55,008 --> 00:24:57,329
And finally, I want it to be balanced, I guess.

393
00:24:57,389 --> 00:25:02,971
I want it to be, you know, feel like it's it's got a space for play in it

394
00:25:03,332 --> 00:25:06,413
so that it doesn't highlight the correct answers, but it doesn't hide them away

395
00:25:06,473 --> 00:25:06,653
either.

396
00:25:10,499 --> 00:25:16,868
So what we really want, I think, is we want to turn the detective game mechanic entirely upside down.

397
00:25:17,815 --> 00:25:22,598
And instead of hunting through a whole possibility space to find the golden path of truth,

398
00:25:22,658 --> 00:25:25,160
the one true meaning that will lead us to the end of the game.

399
00:25:26,001 --> 00:25:30,283
What I want to be doing is I want to be building up a truth a few pieces at a time,

400
00:25:30,784 --> 00:25:37,468
ideally with each piece going in and being examined and tested for its suitability and considered before the next one is applied.

401
00:25:37,828 --> 00:25:43,232
I want to move away from the paradigm of the combination lock.

402
00:25:45,545 --> 00:25:48,946
Towards something that's a lot more like solving a maze.

403
00:25:50,327 --> 00:25:52,167
So in a maze, you have dead ends,

404
00:25:52,227 --> 00:25:53,487
but you can walk back from them.

405
00:25:54,288 --> 00:25:56,148
There doesn't need to be a single path through a maze.

406
00:25:56,168 --> 00:25:58,349
You can do it quickly or slowly.

407
00:25:58,389 --> 00:25:59,349
It doesn't actually matter.

408
00:25:59,389 --> 00:26:01,750
There might be multiple exit points in this maze.

409
00:26:02,010 --> 00:26:03,430
You're just forming a path.

410
00:26:03,710 --> 00:26:04,350
There are rules.

411
00:26:04,370 --> 00:26:05,771
You're not allowed to jump over the walls,

412
00:26:06,151 --> 00:26:08,091
but there's not many more rules than that.

413
00:26:08,812 --> 00:26:13,653
In short, you're constructing an argument, and there is no one right argument for anything,

414
00:26:14,594 --> 00:26:18,515
even something which is entirely self-evident, like that the Russian military action in Ukraine

415
00:26:18,575 --> 00:26:22,497
is a crime against humanity. There are multiple ways to prove that idea. There are multiple

416
00:26:22,537 --> 00:26:26,138
approaches to make that convincing. There is no one way because it's truth, and truth can be

417
00:26:26,178 --> 00:26:30,260
approached from any angle you like. So all we really want to be able to do is make a case that's

418
00:26:30,300 --> 00:26:34,242
compelling and that's watertight and covers the available facts.

419
00:26:35,265 --> 00:26:41,210
We want to step away from this idea that the player is the master detective in control of everything, totally in charge,

420
00:26:41,610 --> 00:26:47,234
because that's not actually that fun. Holmes is not really having that much fun when he just knows the answers.

421
00:26:47,454 --> 00:26:52,278
It's a bit like sitting down to do your Sudoku and being able to see all the numbers in the grid before you've actually done any thinking.

422
00:26:52,318 --> 00:26:53,459
It's pointless at that stage.

423
00:26:54,179 --> 00:26:56,040
I was glib earlier when my slide suggested

424
00:26:56,060 --> 00:26:56,940
that Sudoku was pointless.

425
00:26:57,000 --> 00:26:58,900
Obviously it's the process of deduction that's fun,

426
00:26:59,261 --> 00:27:01,261
but Holmes doesn't get to do that really,

427
00:27:01,281 --> 00:27:02,181
because he just knows,

428
00:27:02,201 --> 00:27:04,002
because otherwise he's not magical Holmes.

429
00:27:04,542 --> 00:27:06,842
So really we want the player to be Watson rather than Holmes,

430
00:27:07,603 --> 00:27:10,223
feeding ideas to his friend,

431
00:27:11,024 --> 00:27:13,024
which his friend will accept or refute.

432
00:27:13,364 --> 00:27:15,925
Doesn't necessarily mean that you need multiple characters.

433
00:27:16,025 --> 00:27:17,345
One protagonist could be going through it

434
00:27:17,385 --> 00:27:18,165
in their own minds.

435
00:27:18,645 --> 00:27:20,466
Poirot is constantly muttering to himself.

436
00:27:20,506 --> 00:27:22,587
So perhaps he's playing the game that we haven't yet made.

437
00:27:23,987 --> 00:27:29,631
And also I think if you think about the design in this way, you start to see opportunities for balancing.

438
00:27:29,651 --> 00:27:36,875
A combination lock cannot be balanced. You either know the answer or you don't. It's like a quiz. It's inherently not fun.

439
00:27:37,889 --> 00:27:42,170
But an argument that's built by playing a game can be balanced.

440
00:27:42,290 --> 00:27:43,690
There can be multiple routes.

441
00:27:43,870 --> 00:27:45,591
The player can redo sections.

442
00:27:45,691 --> 00:27:49,051
The player can be encouraged to improve a semi-coherent idea

443
00:27:49,432 --> 00:27:50,852
into a fully coherent idea.

444
00:27:52,152 --> 00:27:54,313
If you are talking to another person, how helpful are they?

