00:40:21,041 --> 00:40:24,824
or theories or counter theories or comments about what Clarissa

683
00:40:24,864 --> 00:40:26,205
might be like as a person.

684
00:40:26,585 --> 00:40:28,946
or whatever it is you think that might get you off the hook.

685
00:40:29,066 --> 00:40:31,647
And they will sometimes work if they make sense.

686
00:40:32,108 --> 00:40:35,069
So because it's not a formalized abstract system,

687
00:40:35,369 --> 00:40:37,691
we can muck about with it basically and put in stuff that we like.

688
00:40:38,691 --> 00:40:44,814
Similarly, we might play a game in which we're so good at this that Veronica has no guilty outcomes and Clarissa has three guilty outcomes,

689
00:40:44,874 --> 00:40:50,017
in which case the detective will spin round and accuse Clarissa of the crime and nothing she says at that point will save her.

690
00:40:50,337 --> 00:40:52,338
And that's fine. And you can gloat all you like.

691
00:40:53,477 --> 00:41:03,001
And again, his dialogue will explain how the particular bits of evidence that were gathered during this playthrough show the incontrovertible truth that Clarissa is definitely guilty.

692
00:41:03,142 --> 00:41:06,843
And of course, that's dynamically constructed, but that's just a text generation problem.

693
00:41:07,003 --> 00:41:11,446
There's no actual design implications there. So we can black box that and again, just make it as good as we want.

694
00:41:12,106 --> 00:41:16,588
And because Overboard is a game about throwing someone off a boat, we have a nice fallback

695
00:41:16,608 --> 00:41:20,390
position. You always need a fallback position, right? You need a way of dealing with sort of

696
00:41:20,590 --> 00:41:25,592
meh outcomes where the player hasn't really done anything very exciting. And in our case, it's,

697
00:41:25,912 --> 00:41:29,914
well, if Veronica's got one guilty outcome and Clarissa's got one guilty outcome and really

698
00:41:29,934 --> 00:41:34,015
there's nothing very exciting or dramatic going on, then it's probably a suicide.

699
00:41:34,617 --> 00:41:38,740
And we have a narrative reason why that's a not very satisfying ending to the story,

700
00:41:39,241 --> 00:41:43,123
which does the job that we need it to do, which is to say to the player, go away and try harder.

701
00:41:44,525 --> 00:41:48,828
So that's cool.

702
00:41:50,015 --> 00:41:57,621
So the basic principle of all of this is a bit like the Holmes and Watson model that I mentioned, right?

703
00:41:58,061 --> 00:42:05,107
Even though it's a game about falsifying a conviction, about faking evidence and constructing a crime,

704
00:42:05,347 --> 00:42:09,490
you are essentially constructing an argument. You're just doing the evidence first as well.

705
00:42:11,171 --> 00:42:15,874
But the crucial thing is that it doesn't cast the player in the role of the master detective,

706
00:42:15,934 --> 00:42:20,196
or kind of the phrase master detective is sort of polluted by Sherlock Holmes really,

707
00:42:20,456 --> 00:42:23,918
because the point is the player is the detective, the player does go out into the world,

708
00:42:24,378 --> 00:42:28,061
asks questions, discovers information, brings it to the attention of other people.

709
00:42:29,161 --> 00:42:34,025
goes to the right place at the right time and solves the various combination locks that the game has to offer.

710
00:42:34,646 --> 00:42:41,111
But the detective doesn't get to be the judge. The detective is not there to assess the quality of the conclusion.

711
00:42:41,832 --> 00:42:43,994
Somebody else does that.

712
00:42:45,055 --> 00:42:50,156
And by the time they come to do that, the player has set up their initial conditions and is just trying to push an argument through,

713
00:42:50,196 --> 00:42:52,757
so construct an argument that the judge will be happy with.

714
00:42:53,197 --> 00:42:56,378
The player is feeding inputs into a system to get the outcome that they want.

715
00:42:56,958 --> 00:43:02,039
And so it's not a combination lock because it doesn't have an input that you are trying to hit.

716
00:43:02,660 --> 00:43:09,962
It's a bit more like giving a set of directions to a little rat before it runs into a maze and seeing which door it comes out of the other side.

717
00:43:10,442 --> 00:43:11,643
There are lots of solutions.

718
00:43:12,003 --> 00:43:14,285
In fact, we don't know how many solutions Overboard has

719
00:43:14,345 --> 00:43:16,887
because why would we care about that information at all?

720
00:43:17,187 --> 00:43:19,990
It's just so long as every solution that we've seen

721
00:43:20,110 --> 00:43:23,392
makes sense and feels fair, then the game works fine

722
00:43:23,412 --> 00:43:24,333
and that's good enough for us.

723
00:43:25,814 --> 00:43:27,996
So that's the sort of broad idea

724
00:43:28,036 --> 00:43:29,417
of how we approached it for Overboard.

725
00:43:30,488 --> 00:43:34,050
And while we were making it, it was mostly just a quick Christie or March.

726
00:43:34,070 --> 00:43:37,512
But the more I look back on it, the more I wonder about how generalizable this is

727
00:43:37,632 --> 00:43:42,374
as an idea for creating a bit of drama in the story of the detective game,

728
00:43:42,834 --> 00:43:46,836
because I think a point that gets lost a lot when we're thinking about detective

729
00:43:46,856 --> 00:43:52,339
stories is the thing that Christie was so confident about in her writing,

730
00:43:52,419 --> 00:43:56,100
that there are two stories in a detective story, not one, but two.

731
00:43:57,748 --> 00:44:01,013
One of them is the story of the crime, the what happened and why.

732
00:44:01,614 --> 00:44:04,559
And then the other one is the story of the detective and the characters

733
00:44:04,599 --> 00:44:07,644
affected by the murder, dealing with the aftermath of the murder

734
00:44:07,764 --> 00:44:09,507
or whatever's happened and solving it.

735
00:44:10,408 --> 00:44:12,670
And that is a valid story. And it's an important one, too.

736
00:44:12,970 --> 00:44:14,670
Christie novels always have a love affair in them.

737
00:44:14,811 --> 00:44:17,052
You can always tell people who are not going to be guilty

738
00:44:17,112 --> 00:44:19,573
because there is always a young couple who fall in love at the end.

739
00:44:19,933 --> 00:44:22,874
That's just standard logic for a story told in that time.

740
00:44:23,875 --> 00:44:25,636
Actually, Conan Doyle does this, too.

741
00:44:26,176 --> 00:44:28,257
Sherlock Holmes stories are structured much less elegantly.

742
00:44:28,457 --> 00:44:30,918
There's like 80 percent of it is Sherlock and Watson running around,

743
00:44:30,958 --> 00:44:33,199
having a fun time on trains and hitting people with sticks.

744
00:44:33,299 --> 00:44:34,320
And then the last 10 percent.

745
00:44:34,660 --> 00:44:39,242
is the guilty party usually sitting down with Holmes over a nice cup of tea and a pipe and

746
00:44:39,302 --> 00:44:42,803
telling him some story about a thing that happened in the colonies which is why he ended up sending

747
00:44:42,843 --> 00:44:45,844
orange pips to this person or murdering this person or writing stick figures on a well.

748
00:44:46,705 --> 00:44:51,166
The two stories are completely separated in Conan Doyle's writing but they're still both there,

749
00:44:51,226 --> 00:44:55,688
there's the adventure we enjoy and then there's the weird colonial rant that Conan Doyle would

750
00:44:55,728 --> 00:45:00,930
like to go on now and they're put side by side. Christie layers them together and then brings

751
00:45:00,970 --> 00:45:03,672
them together in a conclusion scene with Poirot doing that.

752
00:45:05,430 --> 00:45:11,719
And the reason that's important is it gives us depth to our world because we have a secret history to be uncovered.

753
00:45:11,979 --> 00:45:14,242
But it also gives us just a tub thumping good adventure.

754
00:45:14,522 --> 00:45:19,389
We get some characters to be with. We get a protagonist moving through a world, exploring and having an adventure.

755
00:45:20,009 --> 00:45:23,971
being a real person in a room full of people in a dramatic, intense situation,

756
00:45:24,011 --> 00:45:27,153
which is generally speaking why mystery stories are enjoyable.

757
00:45:27,573 --> 00:45:30,154
It's if you think about the mysteries that you watch on TV,

758
00:45:30,214 --> 00:45:33,035
especially the ones made by ABC Studios,

759
00:45:33,756 --> 00:45:37,117
you've got to remember that the backstory part is never as interesting

760
00:45:37,157 --> 00:45:37,878
as the story part.

761
00:45:37,898 --> 00:45:39,198
We're rooting for the detective.

762
00:45:39,238 --> 00:45:40,479
We're rooting for the characters.

763
00:45:40,599 --> 00:45:41,560
And oh, yeah, there's this mystery.

764
00:45:41,580 --> 00:45:42,800
And we kind of want to know what happened,

765
00:45:42,840 --> 00:45:45,641
but it's rarely the focus of of our engagement.

766
00:45:47,662 --> 00:45:48,323
So I think it's pretty cool.

767
00:45:49,208 --> 00:45:50,590
I guess that's what I'm saying. I think it's pretty cool.

768
00:45:51,330 --> 00:45:52,411
A few other notes on the design.

769
00:45:53,552 --> 00:45:54,794
Firstly, it feels quite natural.

770
00:45:55,054 --> 00:45:57,376
Like writing it was not a big theoretical,

771
00:45:57,396 --> 00:45:58,377
complicated exercise.

772
00:45:58,417 --> 00:46:01,219
There's no weird UI to be assimilated.

773
00:46:01,359 --> 00:46:03,421
We don't have to really tutorialize anything

774
00:46:03,501 --> 00:46:05,383
because it's just people talking to each other.

775
00:46:05,904 --> 00:46:08,045
The player gathers some material, they present it,

776
00:46:08,286 --> 00:46:09,987
it's assessed, and if it's not good enough,

777
00:46:10,167 --> 00:46:12,049
they get sent back to find some more

778
00:46:12,269 --> 00:46:13,871
until they have something which is convincing.

779
00:46:15,032 --> 00:46:15,692
It feels to me...

780
00:46:16,773 --> 00:46:20,335
weirdly like a really familiar design, except I can't actually think of anywhere I've seen it before,

781
00:46:20,375 --> 00:46:22,857
except possibly in the two Infocom games that I mentioned at the start of the talk.

782
00:46:22,897 --> 00:46:25,418
There are no new ideas in game design, right?

783
00:46:25,558 --> 00:46:29,901
The second thing I want to note is that Overboard is very definitely replay to win.

784
00:46:30,081 --> 00:46:32,442
It's structured to put this conversation at the climax.

785
00:46:32,482 --> 00:46:33,183
And if you go wrong.

786
00:46:33,654 --> 00:46:38,940
You get thrown into jail or throw yourself off a boat and you try again with different starting parameters until you get it right.

787
00:46:39,680 --> 00:46:45,907
But it doesn't have to be that way. There's nothing about this design which is inherently a replay to learn game.

788
00:46:46,287 --> 00:46:52,934
You could, for example, play the detective who phones up the police chief to explain what they've learnt so far and lays out the case as they see it.

789
00:46:53,054 --> 00:46:56,598
And the police chief says, no, I'm not sure about that bit. You need more evidence for this.

790
00:46:57,738 --> 00:47:00,819
We can't get arrest because we haven't got enough data on that, that and that.

791
00:47:00,859 --> 00:47:01,580
Go away and get me more.

792
00:47:01,800 --> 00:47:03,000
And then you come back and you get some more.

793
00:47:03,421 --> 00:47:05,162
In that case, a failed state isn't being sent to prison.

794
00:47:05,202 --> 00:47:08,023
It's just let's start from the top or let's look around some more.

795
00:47:08,083 --> 00:47:09,043
Call me back in an hour.

796
00:47:10,984 --> 00:47:15,947
And it doesn't have to be dialogue like I did it through dialogue because I like

797
00:47:15,987 --> 00:47:20,309
dialogue, but and it's fairly natural way to present this idea.

798
00:47:20,389 --> 00:47:24,971
But for people who like you, I and they like connecting boxes and filling things in.

799
00:47:26,108 --> 00:47:28,489
you could imagine a proforma where you say,

800
00:47:28,709 --> 00:47:31,790
so, I don't know, blank went here and did blank,

801
00:47:31,810 --> 00:47:32,811
and then you drag in the blank,

802
00:47:32,851 --> 00:47:33,791
and you drag in the next blank,

803
00:47:33,811 --> 00:47:35,832
and then that unravels into a next bit of conversation.

804
00:47:36,132 --> 00:47:38,853
And the story unfolds depending on exactly

