00:47:39,173 --> 00:47:40,894
how you feed it, right?

806
00:47:41,674 --> 00:47:43,475
I have a suspicion this is what Veilbetter's

807
00:47:43,695 --> 00:47:46,096
Mask of the Rose deduction system is gonna be like,

808
00:47:46,116 --> 00:47:47,217
but I haven't actually played that demo enough

809
00:47:47,277 --> 00:47:48,037
to be sure about that.

810
00:47:48,077 --> 00:47:48,477
So we'll see.

811
00:47:50,958 --> 00:47:52,699
Such a system, if you built it that way,

812
00:47:53,439 --> 00:47:54,440
would still be curated.

813
00:47:55,072 --> 00:47:58,233
It's still filtering the options down to make sure that I don't get overloaded.

814
00:47:58,333 --> 00:48:01,414
It's still building an argument organically from the ground up.

815
00:48:01,454 --> 00:48:05,795
It's perhaps a little bit more constrained in its structure, but it's not very constrained.

816
00:48:05,835 --> 00:48:10,477
It's certainly not so rigid that it has to be fact one plus fact two equals fact three or nothing.

817
00:48:10,497 --> 00:48:16,719
And it is capable of expressing different kinds of ideas or bringing in ideas from the real world or bringing in new ideas.

818
00:48:16,959 --> 00:48:20,100
There's no reason you can't drag in ladies button their coats left over, right?

819
00:48:20,280 --> 00:48:21,940
If it seems like a relevant thing to drag in.

820
00:48:22,707 --> 00:48:27,802
And it will be a surprising moment, if perhaps a fairly obvious one in the context of that instance of the game.

821
00:48:29,180 --> 00:48:34,702
Finally, the correct path can be very broad, which I think ultimately we have to agree that that's probably a good thing,

822
00:48:34,782 --> 00:48:39,023
because frustration in detective games is a real problem and truth is a big, broad concept.

823
00:48:39,043 --> 00:48:42,764
There shouldn't really be a single solution path. It doesn't make a lot of sense.

824
00:48:42,784 --> 00:48:45,664
And every time I try to write one, it just goes wrong because it's ludicrous.

825
00:48:45,704 --> 00:48:54,927
Right. So we're effectively talking about something which is a kind of simulation, though it depends how you build it exactly, but a simulation of an argument.

826
00:48:55,504 --> 00:48:59,986
not a branching tree narrative in which you die on these instances and you don't die on that instance.

827
00:49:01,547 --> 00:49:06,930
So to summarise all of that, to put all of that together, I think it's like I said earlier,

828
00:49:07,210 --> 00:49:12,332
I want to get away from this idea that the combination lock is the.

829
00:49:13,284 --> 00:49:18,927
core model of what the detective does, that the detective is constantly cracking a correct

830
00:49:19,007 --> 00:49:24,430
answer from a set of impossible answers. Away from Sherlock Holmes and his, when you've removed

831
00:49:24,510 --> 00:49:28,111
everything that's impossible, then whatever remains, however improbable, must be the truth.

832
00:49:28,171 --> 00:49:32,614
Which, you know, fine, yes, that's true, but that's not the most interesting way to solve

833
00:49:32,694 --> 00:49:36,796
a detective narrative. It's not the most sparkling conclusion to a narrative. It is the five in the

834
00:49:36,816 --> 00:49:38,276
middle of the sudoku, which...

835
00:49:39,292 --> 00:49:40,373
is a perfectly good solution.

836
00:49:40,613 --> 00:49:41,074
It'll do.

837
00:49:41,214 --> 00:49:43,195
It sort of says, well, when you've tried everything,

838
00:49:43,235 --> 00:49:44,476
you might as well go with this one.

839
00:49:44,857 --> 00:49:47,258
It's a bit like, I don't know. Yeah, it's not.

840
00:49:47,278 --> 00:49:49,620
It's not very it doesn't fill me with excitement, really.

841
00:49:49,880 --> 00:49:51,382
The great thing about the end of a Poirot novel

842
00:49:51,622 --> 00:49:53,443
is that when Poirot turns around and accuses someone,

843
00:49:53,463 --> 00:49:55,645
it's always the person who it obviously was from the beginning.

844
00:49:55,725 --> 00:49:57,967
And Poirot's argument is usually, I knew that you did it.

845
00:49:58,267 --> 00:50:00,328
You're the only person in this room capable of murder.

846
00:50:00,589 --> 00:50:01,990
But then I had to figure out how and why.

847
00:50:02,730 --> 00:50:04,011
And there's something really nice about that.

848
00:50:04,031 --> 00:50:06,193
There's something really solid and charming about that, I think.

849
00:50:07,146 --> 00:50:09,726
So let's move away from deduction.

850
00:50:10,527 --> 00:50:12,407
Deduction means taking things away.

851
00:50:12,827 --> 00:50:13,747
Let's stop doing that.

852
00:50:14,007 --> 00:50:15,588
Let's move towards construction,

853
00:50:15,888 --> 00:50:19,388
towards building and growing and developing a narrative

854
00:50:19,448 --> 00:50:22,009
that we can be part of and we can be excited about.

855
00:50:23,029 --> 00:50:24,810
That's what I think we should be doing for Detective Games.

856
00:50:25,490 --> 00:50:26,170
Thank you for listening.

857
00:50:26,210 --> 00:50:29,411
I will attempt to take questions over the magical internet,

